"[[.l1celist" <- function(x, ..., drop = T){
X
X  class(x) <- NULL
X  val <- NextMethod("[[")
X  if( !length(val) ) return (NULL)
X
X  xattr <- attributes(x)
X  nattr <- names(xattr)
X  val[nattr] <- xattr[nattr]
X
X  class(val) <- "l1ce"
X  val
}
X
"[.l1celist" <- function(x, ..., drop = T){
X
X  class(x) <- NULL
X  val <- NextMethod("[")
X  junk <- do.call("c", lapply(val,length))
X  val <- val[junk!=0]
X  if( !length(val) ) return (NULL)
X  if( drop && length(val)==1 ){
X    val <- val[[1]]
X    
X    xattr <- attributes(x)
X    nattr <- names(xattr)
X    val[nattr] <- xattr[nattr]
X
X    class(val) <- "l1ce"
X    val
X  }else{
X    attributes(val) <- attributes(x)
X    class(val) <- "l1celist"
X    val
X  }
}
X
aux <- function(object)
X  UseMethod("aux")
X
aux.l1celist <- function(object, ...){
X
X  res1 <- do.call("c", lapply(object, "[[", "relative.bound"))
X  res2 <- do.call("c", lapply(object, "[[", "bound"))
X  res3 <- do.call("c", lapply(object, "[[", "Lagrangian"))
X
X  if( is.null(res1) ){
X    structure(cbind(res2,res3),
X              dimnames=list(NULL, c("abs.bound", "Lagrangian")))
X  }else{
X    structure(cbind(res1, res2,res3),
X              dimnames=list(NULL, c("rel.bound", "abs.bound",
X                "Lagrangian")))
X  }
}
X
tr <- function(mat){
X
X  dims <- dim(mat)
X  if((length(dims) !=2) || dims[1]!=dims[2])
X    stop("This function is only defined for square matrices")
X
X  sum(diag(mat))
}

plot.l1celist <- function(object, plot=T, all=T, constrained=F, ...){
X  bounds <- aux(object)
X  mat.of.coef <- coef(object, all=all, constrained = constrained)
X
X  if(plot) {
X    matplot(bounds[, 1], mat.of.coef, ...)
X    rug(bounds[, 1])
X  }
X
X  invisible(list(bounds=bounds,
X                 mat.of.coef=mat.of.coef))
}

###  Copyright (C) 1998
###  Justin Lokhorst <jlokhors@stats.adelaide.edu.au>

###  MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
###  Library General Public License for more details.

###  License along with this library; if not, write to the Free Software
###  Foundation, Inc., 59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, 
###  MA 02111-1307 USA
predict.l1ce <- function(object, newdata, type=c("response"), se.fit = F)
{
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X  if(missing(newdata))
X    return(object$fitted)
X  if(se.fit)
X    stop("The \"se.fit\" argument is not currently implemented for l1ce objects")
X  
X  tt <- object$terms
X  if(!inherits(tt, "terms"))
X    stop("invalid terms component of  fit")
X  offset <- attr(tt, "offset")
X  intercept <- attr(tt, "intercept")
X
X  if(missing(newdata)) {
X    x <- model.matrix(object)
X  }else if(!((is.atomic(newdata) && length(newdata) == 1
X              && length(object$coef) != 1 && newdata > 0
X              && (newdata - trunc(newdata) < .Machine$single.eps))
X             | is.list(newdata))) {
X    ## try and coerce newdata to look like the x matrix
X    if(!is.null(offset)) {
X      warning("Offset not included")
X      offset <- NULL
X    }
X    TT <- length(object$coef)
X    if(is.matrix(newdata) && ncol(newdata) == TT)
X      x <- newdata
X      else if(length(newdata) == TT)
X        x <- matrix(newdata, 1, TT)
X        else stop("Argument \"newdata\" is not a data frame, and cannot be coerced to an appropriate model matrix")
X  }else {
X    ##newdata is a list, data frame or frame number
X    vv <- attr(tt, "variables")
X    attr(tt, "variables") <- vv[ - attr(tt, "response")]
X    x <- model.matrix(tt, newdata, object$contrasts)
X    if(!is.null(offset))
X      offset <- eval(attr(tt, "variables")[offset], newdata)
X  }
X
X  coefs <- coef(object)
X  pred <- drop( x%*% coefs )
X  if(!is.null(offset)) {
X    if(missing(newdata))
X      warning("Offset not included")
X      else {
X        pred <- pred + offset
X      }
X  }
X  pred
}
X
predict.gl1ce <- function(object, newdata, type=c("link", "response"),
X                          se.fit = F, ...)
{
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X  if(!se.fit){
X    if (missing(newdata)) {
X      switch(type,
X             link = object$linear.predictors,
X             response = object$fitted)
X    }else{
X      switch(type,
X             response = family(object)$inverse(NextMethod("predict")),
X             link = {
X               type <- "response"
X               NextMethod("predict")
X             })
X    }
X  }else{
X    stop("The \"se.fit\" argument is not currently implemented for gl1ce objects")
X  }
}
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 1209101399 'Lasso2/predict.q' &&
  chmod 0444 'Lasso2/predict.q' ||
  echo 'restore of Lasso2/predict.q failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Lasso2/predict.q'`"
  test 3177 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/predict.q: original size 3177, current size $shar_count"
fi

  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Lasso2/print.q' &&
###  Copyright (C) 1998
###  Justin Lokhorst <jlokhors@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Berwin A. Turlach <bturlach@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Bill Venables <wvenable@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###
###  This library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or
###  modify it under the terms of the GNU Library General Public
###  License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either
###  version 2 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.
###
###  This library is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,
###  but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
###  MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
###  Library General Public License for more details.
###
###  You should have received a copy of the GNU Library General Public
###  License along with this library; if not, write to the Free Software
###  Foundation, Inc., 59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, 
###  MA 02111-1307 USA
print.l1ce <- function(x, ...){
X  
X  if(!is.null(cl <- x$call)) {
X    cat("Call:\n")
X    dput(cl)
X  }
X  
X  cat("\nCoefficients:\n")
X  print(coef(x), ...)
X
X  if(!is.null(rel <- x$relative.bound)){
X    cat("\nThe relative L1 bound was      :", format(rel), "\n")
X  }else{
X    cat("\n")
X  }
X  cat("The absolute L1 bound was      :", format(x$bound), "\n")
X  cat("The Lagrangian for the bound is: ",
X      format(x$Lagrangian), "\n")
X
X  if(!is.null(attr(x, "na.message")))
X    cat("\n", attr(x, "na.message"), "\n")
X
X  invisible(x)
}
X
print.l1celist <- function(x, ...){
X  
X  if(!is.null(cl <- attr(x, "call"))) {
X    cat("Call:\n")
X    dput(cl)
X  }
X
X  mat.of.coef <- coef(x)
X  cat("\nCoefficients:\n")
X  print(mat.of.coef, ...)
X
X  x.aux <- aux(x)
X  if( ncol(x.aux) == 2 ){
X    cat("\nAbsolute L1 bounds and the Lagrangians:\n")
X    print(x.aux, ...)
X  }else{
X    cat("\nRelative and absolute L1 bounds and the Lagrangians:\n")
X    print(x.aux, ...)
X  }
X
X  if(!is.null(attr(x, "na.message")))
X    cat("\n", attr(x, "na.message"), "\n")
X
X  invisible(x)
}
X
print.summary.l1ce <- function(x,
X                               digits = max(3, .Options$digits - 3),
X                               ...)
{
X  cat("\nCall:\n ")
X  dput(x$call)
X  resid <- x$residuals
X  df <- x$df
X  rdf <- df[2]
X  if(rdf > 5) {
X    cat("Residuals:\n")
X    if(length(dim(resid)) == 2) {
X      rq <- apply(t(resid), 1, quantile)
X      dimnames(rq) <- list(c("Min", "1Q", "Median", "3Q", 
X                             "Max"), dimnames(resid)[[2]])
X    }
X      else {
X        rq <- quantile(resid)
X        names(rq) <- c("Min", "1Q", "Median", "3Q", "Max")
X      }
X    print(rq, digits = digits, ...)
X  }
X    else if(rdf > 0) {
X      cat("Residuals:\n")
X      print(resid, digits = digits, ...)
X    }
X  cat("\nCoefficients:\n")
X  print(format(round(x$coef, digits = digits)), quote = F, ...)
X  if(x$sigma.provided){
X    cat("\nResidual standard error:",
X        format(signif(x$sigma, digits)),
X        "was provided to \"summary.l1ce\"\n")
X  }else{
X    cat("\nResidual standard error:",
X        format(signif(x$sigma, digits)),
X        "on", format(signif(rdf,digits)), "degrees of freedom\n")
X  }
X  if(!is.null(rel <- x$relative.bound))
X    cat("The relative L1 bound was      :", format(rel), "\n")
X  cat("The absolute L1 bound was      :", format(x$bound), "\n")
X  cat("The Lagrangian for the bound is: ",
X      format(x$Lagrangian), "\n")
X
X  correl <- x$correlation
X  if(!is.null(correl)) {
X    p <- dim(correl)[2]
X    if(p > 1) {
X      cat("\nCorrelation of Coefficients:\n")
X      ll <- lower.tri(correl)
X      correl[ll] <- format(round(correl[ll], digits))
X      correl[!ll] <- ""
X      print(correl[-1,  - p, drop = F], quote = F, digits = 
X            digits, ...)
X    }
X  }
X  invisible(x)
X  
}
X
print.gl1ce <- function(x, ...) {
X  if(!is.null(cl <- x$call)) {
X    cat("Call:\n")
X    dput(cl)
X  }
X
X  cat("\nCoefficients:\n")
X  print(coef(x), ...)
X
X  cat("\nFamily:\n")
X  print(x$family, ...)
X
X  cat("\nThe absolute L1 bound was       : ", format(x$bound), "\n")
X  cat("The Lagrangian for the bound is : ", format(x$Lagrangian), "\n")
X
X  if(!is.null(attr(x, "na.message")))
X    cat("\n", attr(x, "na.message"), "\n")
X
X  invisible(x)
}
X
print.summary.gl1ce <- function(x,
X                                digits = max(3, .Options$digits - 3),          
X                                ...) {
X  cat("\nCall:\n")
X  dput(x$call)
X  resid <- residuals(x)
X  cat("\nDeviance Residuals:\n")
X  if(length(dim(resid)) == 2) {
X    rq <- apply(t(resid), 1, quantile)
X    dimnames(rq) <- list(c("Min", "1Q", "Median", "3Q", "Max"),
X                         dimnames(resid)[[2]])
X  }else{
X    rq <- quantile(resid)
X    names(rq) <- c("Min", "1Q", "Median", "3Q", "Max")
X  }
X  print(rq, digits = digits)
X  cat("\nCoefficients\n")
X  print(format(round(t(x$coeff), digits = digits)), quote = F, ...)
X  
X  cat("\nFamily:\n")
X  print(x$family, ...)
X
X  cat("\nThe absolute L1 bound was     : ", format(x$bound), "\n")
X  cat("The Lagrangian for the bound is : ", format(x$Lagrangian), "\n") 
X
X  cat("\nNumber of Iterations:", format(trunc(x$iter)), "\n")
X
X  invisible(x)
}
X
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 1209101399 'Lasso2/print.q' &&
  chmod 0444 'Lasso2/print.q' ||
  echo 'restore of Lasso2/print.q failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Lasso2/print.q'`"
  test 5077 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/print.q: original size 5077, current size $shar_count"

# ============= Lasso2/residuals.q ==============
if test -f 'Lasso2/residuals.q' && test X"$1" != X"-c"; then
  echo 'x - skipping Lasso2/residuals.q (File already exists)'
else
  echo 'x - extracting Lasso2/residuals.q (text)'
  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Lasso2/residuals.q' &&
###  Copyright (C) 1998, 1999
###  Justin Lokhorst <jlokhors@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Berwin A. Turlach <bturlach@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Bill Venables <wvenable@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###
###  This library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or
###  modify it under the terms of the GNU Library General Public
###  License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either
###  version 2 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.
###
###  This library is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,
###  but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
###  MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
###  Library General Public License for more details.
###
###  You should have received a copy of the GNU Library General Public
###  License along with this library; if not, write to the Free Software
###  Foundation, Inc., 59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, 
###  MA 02111-1307 USA
residuals.l1ce <- function(object,
X                           type = c("working", "pearson", "deviance")){
X                             
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X  switch(type,
X         working = object$residuals,
X         pearson =, deviance =
X         if(is.null(object$weights)) object$residuals else 
X         residuals.glm(object, "pearson")
X         )
}
X
residuals.l1celist <- function(object,
X                               type = c("working", "pearson", "deviance")){
X                             
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X  resid <- do.call("cbind", lapply(object, "[[", "residuals"))
X  weights <- attr(object, "weights")
X  switch(type,
X         working = resid,
X         pearson =, deviance =
X         if(is.null(weights)) resid else 
X         sqrt(weights)*resid
X         )
}
X
residuals.gl1ce <- function(object,
X                            type = c("deviance", "pearson", "working",
X                              "response"))
{
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X  switch(type,
X         working = object$residuals,
X         pearson = sqrt(object$weights) * object$residuals,
X         deviance = {
X           y <- object$y
X           mu <- object$fitted
X           family <- object$family
X           w <- object$prior.weights
X           if(is.null(w))
X             w <- rep(1, length(mu))
X           family$deviance(mu, y, w, residuals=T)
X         },
X         response = object$y - fitted(object) )
} 
X
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 1209101399 'Lasso2/residuals.q' &&
  chmod 0444 'Lasso2/residuals.q' ||
  echo 'restore of Lasso2/residuals.q failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Lasso2/residuals.q'`"
  test 2368 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/residuals.q: original size 2368, current size $shar_count"
fi
# ============= Lasso2/summary.q ==============
if test -f 'Lasso2/summary.q' && test X"$1" != X"-c"; then
  echo 'x - skipping Lasso2/summary.q (File already exists)'
else
  echo 'x - extracting Lasso2/summary.q (text)'
  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Lasso2/summary.q' &&
###  Copyright (C) 1998, 1999
###  Justin Lokhorst <jlokhors@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Berwin A. Turlach <bturlach@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Bill Venables <wvenable@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###
###  This library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or
###  modify it under the terms of the GNU Library General Public
###  License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either
###  version 2 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.
###
###  This library is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,
###  but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
###  MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
###  Library General Public License for more details.
###
###  You should have received a copy of the GNU Library General Public
###  License along with this library; if not, write to the Free Software
###  Foundation, Inc., 59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, 
###  MA 02111-1307 USA
summary.l1ce <- function(object,
X                         correlation = T,
X                         type = c("OPT", "Tibshirani"),
X                         gen.inverse.diag = 0,
X                         sigma = NULL)
{
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X  
X  coef <- coef(object)
X  cnames <- labels(coef)
X  resid <- resid(object)
X  fv <- fitted(object)
X
X  covdf <- vcov(object,type,gen.inverse.diag)
X  sigma.provided <- T
X  if(missing(sigma)){
X    sigma <- sqrt(deviance(object)/covdf$df[2])
X    sigma.provided <- F
X  }
X  se <- as.vector(sqrt(diag(covdf$cov.unscaled)))
X
X  if(correlation) {
X    p  <- length(se)
X    correl <- covdf$cov.unscaled/se
X    correl <- correl/se[rep(1:p,rep(p,p))]
X  }else{
X    correl <- NULL
X  }
X
X  coef <- array(coef, c(p, 4))
X  dimnames(coef) <- list(cnames,
X                         c("Value", "Std. Error", "Z score", "Pr(>|Z|)")) 
X  coef[, 2] <- se %o% sigma
X  coef[, 3] <- coef[, 1]/coef[, 2]
X  coef[, 4] <- 2*(1-pnorm(abs(coef[,3])))
X
X  keep <- c("call", "terms", "bound", "relative.bound", "Lagrangian")
X  object <- object[keep[!is.na(match(keep,names(object)))]]
X  object$residuals <- resid
X  object$coefficients <- coef
X  object$sigma <- sigma
X  object$sigma.provided <- sigma.provided
X  object$df <- covdf$df
X  object$cov.unscaled <- covdf$cov.unscaled
X  object$correlation <- correl
X  class(object) <- "summary.l1ce"
X  object
}
X
summary.gl1ce <- function(object,
X                          dispersion = NULL,
X                          correlation=F)
{
X  if(correlation) {
X    stop(paste("The \"correlation\" argument is not currently implemented",
X               " for gl1ce objects", sep=""))
X  }
X  coef <- coef(object)
X  cnames <- labels(object)
X  resid <- residuals(object, type="deviance")
X  fv <- fitted(object)
X  family <- object$family
X  iter <- object$iter
X  coef <- array(coef, length(coef))
X  dimnames(coef) <- list(c("(Intercept)",cnames))
X
X  keep <- c("call", "terms", "bound", "Lagrangian")
X  object <- object[keep[!is.na(match(keep, names(object)))]]
X  object$residuals <- resid
X  object$coefficients <- coef
X  object$family <- family
X  object$iter <- iter
X  class(object) <- "summary.gl1ce"
X
X  object
}
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 1209101399 'Lasso2/summary.q' &&
  chmod 0444 'Lasso2/summary.q' ||
  echo 'restore of Lasso2/summary.q failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Lasso2/summary.q'`"
  test 3108 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/summary.q: original size 3108, current size $shar_count"
fi

  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Lasso2/vcov.q' &&
###  Copyright (C) 1998
###  Berwin A. Turlach <bturlach@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###  Bill Venables <wvenable@stats.adelaide.edu.au>
###
###  This library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or
###  modify it under the terms of the GNU Library General Public
###  License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either
###  version 2 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.
###
###  This library is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,
###  but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
###  MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
###  Library General Public License for more details.
###
###  You should have received a copy of the GNU Library General Public
###  License along with this library; if not, write to the Free Software
###  Foundation, Inc., 59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, 
###  MA 02111-1307 USA
vcov <- function(object, ...)
X  UseMethod("vcov")
X
vcov.l1ce <- function(object,
X                      type = c("OPT", "Tibshirani"),
X                      gen.inverse.diag = 0)
{
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X
X  xtx <- object$xtx
X  cov.mat <- switch(type,
X                    OPT = opt.covmat(xtx, object$xtr, object$bound,
X                      object$Lagrangian), 
X                    Tibshirani = tib.covmat(xtx, gen.inverse.diag,
X                      object$constrained.coefficients, object$Lagrangian)
X                    )
X  cov.mat <- solve(cov.mat)
X  df <- tr(junk<-cov.mat%*%xtx)
X  cov.mat <- junk%*%cov.mat
X
X  if(!is.null(object$X.stds)){
X    X.stds <- as.vector(object$X.stds)
X    p <- length(X.stds)
X    cov.mat <- cov.mat/X.stds
X    cov.mat <- cov.mat/X.stds[rep(1:p,rep(p,p))]
X  }
X
X  if(!is.null(object$sweep.out)){
X    if(!object$sweep.out$all.matched)
X      warning("Variables in sweep.out were not a subset of variables in model.  Results could be meaningless.")
X
X    psi1 <- object$sweep.out$X.so.rtr.inv
X    psi2 <- cov.mat
X    psi12 <- object$sweep.out$X.so.X %*% psi2
X    psi1 <- psi1 + psi12 %*% t(object$sweep.out$X.so.X)
X
X    p1 <- nrow(psi1)
X    p2 <- nrow(psi2)
X    cov.mat <- matrix(0,p1+p2,p1+p2)
X    cov.mat[1:p1,1:p1] <- psi1
X    cov.mat[(p1+1):(p1+p2),(p1+1):(p1+p2)] <- psi2
X    cov.mat[(p1+1):(p1+p2),1:p1] <- -t(psi12)
X    cov.mat[1:p1,(p1+1):(p1+p2)] <- -psi12
X    
X    names1 <- do.call("c",dimnames(object$sweep.out$X.so.X))
X    dimnames(cov.mat) <- list(names1, names1)
X    names2 <- names(object$coefficients)
X    cov.mat <- cov.mat[names2,names2]
X    df <- df+p1
X  }
X  list(cov.unscaled=cov.mat,
X       df = c(df,length(object$fitted)-df))
}
X
vcov.l1celist <- function(object,
X                          type = c("OPT", "Tibshirani"),
X                          gen.inverse.diag = 0)
{
X  type <- match.arg(type)
X
X  res <- list()
X  for(i in 1:length(object))
X    res[[i]] <- vcov(object[[i]],type,gen.inverse.diag)
X  res
}
X
opt.covmat <- function(xtx, xtr, bound, Lagrangian)
{
X  if( bound == 0 )
X    stop("\"bound\" must be unequal zero when calculating covariance matrix")
X  if( abs(Lagrangian) < sqrt(.Machine$double.eps) ){
X    xtx
X  }else{
X    xtx + xtr%*%t(xtr)/(bound*Lagrangian)
X  }
}
X
tib.covmat <- function(xtx, gen.inverse.diag, beta, Lagrangian)
{
X  ind <- abs(beta) > sqrt(.Machine$double.eps)
X  beta[ind]  <- 1/abs(beta[ind])
X  beta[!ind] <- gen.inverse.diag
X
X  xtx + Lagrangian*diag(beta)
}
X

  test 3347 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/vcov.q: original size 3347, current size $shar_count"
fi

#define S_Plus
#ifndef BT_LASSO_H
#define BT_LASSO_H
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <float.h>
#if defined(S_Plus)
#include <S.h>
#if defined(SPLUS_VERSION) && SPLUS_VERSION >= 4000
#  include <newredef.h>
#endif
#endif
void lasso(double *x, long *pn, long *pm, double *pt,
X           double *beta, double *y, double *yhat1, double *r,
X           double *lagrangian, long *psuc,  long *pverb, long *pas_sub);
void mult_lasso(double *x, long *pn, long *pm, double *pt, long *pl,
X                double *beta, double *y, double *yhat1, double *r,
X                double *lagrangian, long *psuc, long *pverb);
void rs_lasso(double *x, double *y, long *pn, long *porder,
X           double *pt, double *beta, double *yhat1,  double *yhat2,
X           double *r, long *psuc, long *pverb, long *pas_sub);
void rs_auto(double *x, double *y, long *pn, long *porder,
X           double *pt, double *beta, double *yhat1, double *yhat2,
X           double *r,  long *pcrit1, double *pprec,
X           long *psuc, long *pverb,
X           double *tgr, double *tgr_val, long *ptgr_len);
#if !defined(S_Plus)
#define Calloc(n,t)       malloc((n)*sizeof(t))
#define Realloc(p,n,t)    realloc(p,(n)*sizeof(t))
#define Free(p)           free(p), p=NULL
#include <strings.h>      
#define Memcpy(p,q,n)     memcpy(p,q,(n)*sizeof(*(p)))
#endif
X
#define TRUE 1
#define FALSE 0
#define RMAT(i,j) (*(rmat+(j)*((j)+1)/2+(i)))
#define QMAT(i,j) (*(qmat+(j)*q_nrow+(i)))
#define RLAST(i)  (*(rmat+(r_ncol-1)*r_ncol/2+(i)))
#define RLTEL     (*(rmat+r_ncol*(r_ncol+1)/2-1))
#define RCOL(j)   (rmat+(j)*((j)+1)/2)
#define QCOL(j)   (qmat+(j)*q_nrow)
#define RLTCOL    (rmat+(r_ncol-1)*r_ncol/2)
#define QR_CHUNK 10
#if defined (S_Plus)
#define ERRMSG(where,msg) errmsg(msg) 
#else                    
#define ERRMSG(where,msg) errmsg(where,msg) 
#endif
#endif

SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 1209101399 'Lasso2/Makefile' &&
  chmod 0644 'Lasso2/Makefile' ||
  echo 'restore of Lasso2/Makefile failed'
  shar_count="`wc -c < 'Lasso2/Makefile'`"
  test 7412 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/Makefile: original size 7412, current size $shar_count"
fi
# ============= Lasso2/COPYING.LIB ==============
if test -f 'Lasso2/COPYING.LIB' && test X"$1" != X"-c"; then
  echo 'x - skipping Lasso2/COPYING.LIB (File already exists)'
else
  echo 'x - extracting Lasso2/COPYING.LIB (text)'
  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Lasso2/COPYING.LIB' &&
X		  GNU LIBRARY GENERAL PUBLIC LICENSE
X		       Version 2, June 1991
X
X Copyright (C) 1991 Free Software Foundation, Inc.
X    		    59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, MA  02111-1307  USA
X Everyone is permitted to copy and distribute verbatim copies
X of this license document, but changing it is not allowed.
X
[This is the first released version of the library GPL.  It is
X numbered 2 because it goes with version 2 of the ordinary GPL.]
X
X			    Preamble
X
X  The licenses for most software are designed to take away your
freedom to share and change it.  By contrast, the GNU General Public
Licenses are intended to guarantee your freedom to share and change
free software--to make sure the software is free for all its users.
X
X  This license, the Library General Public License, applies to some
specially designated Free Software Foundation software, and to any
other libraries whose authors decide to use it.  You can use it for
your libraries, too.
X
X  When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom, not
price.  Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that you
have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge for
this service if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it
if you want it, that you can change the software or use pieces of it
in new free programs; and that you know you can do these things.
X
X  To protect your rights, we need to make restrictions that forbid
anyone to deny you these rights or to ask you to surrender the rights.
These restrictions translate to certain responsibilities for you if
you distribute copies of the library, or if you modify it.
X
X  For example, if you distribute copies of the library, whether gratis
or for a fee, you must give the recipients all the rights that we gave
you.  You must make sure that they, too, receive or can get the source
code.  If you link a program with the library, you must provide
complete object files to the recipients so that they can relink them
with the library, after making changes to the library and recompiling
it.  And you must show them these terms so they know their rights.
X
X  Our method of protecting your rights has two steps: (1) copyright
the library, and (2) offer you this license which gives you legal
permission to copy, distribute and/or modify the library.
X
X  Also, for each distributor's protection, we want to make certain
that everyone understands that there is no warranty for this free
library.  If the library is modified by someone else and passed on, we
want its recipients to know that what they have is not the original
version, so that any problems introduced by others will not reflect on
the original authors' reputations.
X
X  Finally, any free program is threatened constantly by software
patents.  We wish to avoid the danger that companies distributing free
software will individually obtain patent licenses, thus in effect
transforming the program into proprietary software.  To prevent this,
we have made it clear that any patent must be licensed for everyone's
free use or not licensed at all.
X
X  Most GNU software, including some libraries, is covered by the ordinary
GNU General Public License, which was designed for utility programs.  This
license, the GNU Library General Public License, applies to certain
designated libraries.  This license is quite different from the ordinary
one; be sure to read it in full, and don't assume that anything in it is
the same as in the ordinary license.
X
X  The reason we have a separate public license for some libraries is that
they blur the distinction we usually make between modifying or adding to a
program and simply using it.  Linking a program with a library, without
changing the library, is in some sense simply using the library, and is
analogous to running a utility program or application program.  However, in
a textual and legal sense, the linked executable is a combined work, a
derivative of the original library, and the ordinary General Public License
treats it as such.
X
X  Because of this blurred distinction, using the ordinary General
Public License for libraries did not effectively promote software
sharing, because most developers did not use the libraries.  We
concluded that weaker conditions might promote sharing better.
X
X  However, unrestricted linking of non-free programs would deprive the
users of those programs of all benefit from the free status of the
libraries themselves.  This Library General Public License is intended to
permit developers of non-free programs to use free libraries, while
preserving your freedom as a user of such programs to change the free
libraries that are incorporated in them.  (We have not seen how to achieve
this as regards changes in header files, but we have achieved it as regards
changes in the actual functions of the Library.)  The hope is that this
will lead to faster development of free libraries.
X
X  The precise terms and conditions for copying, distribution and
modification follow.  Pay close attention to the difference between a
"work based on the library" and a "work that uses the library".  The
former contains code derived from the library, while the latter only
works together with the library.
X
X  Note that it is possible for a library to be covered by the ordinary
General Public License rather than by this special one.
X
X		  GNU LIBRARY GENERAL PUBLIC LICENSE
X   TERMS AND CONDITIONS FOR COPYING, DISTRIBUTION AND MODIFICATION
X
X  0. This License Agreement applies to any software library which
contains a notice placed by the copyright holder or other authorized
party saying it may be distributed under the terms of this Library
General Public License (also called "this License").  Each licensee is
addressed as "you".
X
X  A "library" means a collection of software functions and/or data
prepared so as to be conveniently linked with application programs
(which use some of those functions and data) to form executables.
X
X  The "Library", below, refers to any such software library or work
which has been distributed under these terms.  A "work based on the
Library" means either the Library or any derivative work under
copyright law: that is to say, a work containing the Library or a
portion of it, either verbatim or with modifications and/or translated
straightforwardly into another language.  (Hereinafter, translation is
included without limitation in the term "modification".)

X  "Source code" for a work means the preferred form of the work for
making modifications to it.  For a library, complete source code means
all the source code for all modules it contains, plus any associated
interface definition files, plus the scripts used to control compilation
and installation of the library.
X
X  Activities other than copying, distribution and modification are not
covered by this License; they are outside its scope.  The act of
running a program using the Library is not restricted, and output from
such a program is covered only if its contents constitute a work based
on the Library (independent of the use of the Library in a tool for
writing it).  Whether that is true depends on what the Library does
and what the program that uses the Library does.

X    its purpose remains meaningful.

X    a purpose that is entirely well-defined independent of the
X    application.  Therefore, Subsection 2d requires that any
X    application-supplied function or table used by this function must
X    be optional: if the application does not supply it, the square
X    root function must still compute square roots.)

These requirements apply to the modified work as a whole.  If
identifiable sections of that work are not derived from the Library,
and can be reasonably considered independent and separate works in
themselves, then this License, and its terms, do not apply to those
sections when you distribute them as separate works.  But when you

this License, whose permissions for other licensees extend to the

X  5. A program that contains no derivative of any portion of the
Library, but is designed to work with the Library by being compiled or
linked with it, is called a "work that uses the Library".  Such a
work, in isolation, is not a derivative work of the Library, and
therefore falls outside the scope of this License.
X
X  However, linking a "work that uses the Library" with the Library
creates an executable that is a derivative of the Library (because it
contains portions of the Library), rather than a "work that uses the
library".  The executable is therefore covered by this License.
Section 6 states terms for distribution of such executables.
X
X  When a "work that uses the Library" uses material from a header file
that is part of the Library, the object code for the work may be a
derivative work of the Library even though the source code is not.
Whether this is true is especially significant if the work can be
linked without the Library, or if the work is itself a library.  The
threshold for this to be true is not precisely defined by law.
X
X  If such an object file uses only numerical parameters, data
structure layouts and accessors, and small macros and small inline
functions (ten lines or less in length), then the use of the object
file is unrestricted, regardless of whether it is legally a derivative
work.  (Executables containing this object code plus portions of the
Library will still fall under Section 6.)
X
X  Otherwise, if the work is a derivative of the Library, you may
distribute the object code for the work under the terms of Section 6.
Any executables containing that work also fall under Section 6,
whether or not they are linked directly with the Library itself.

L1 constrained estimation functions for S-plus
X
l1ce(...)               Solve a regression problem under L1 constraints
X                        on parameters
gl1ce(...)              Solve a generalised linear model rgression
X                        problem under L1 constraints on parameters

This library contains routines and documentation for solving
regression problems while imposing an L1 constraint on the estimates.
The code is based on the algorithm of Osborne et al. (1998) and is
distributed in the hope that they may also be useful to others.
However, this software is provided "as is" without any expressed or
implied warranty.  Specifically:
X
X    This library is free software; you can redistribute it and/or
X    modify it under the terms of the GNU Library General Public
X    License as published by the Free Software Foundation; either
X    version 2 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.
X    
X    This library is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,
X    but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
X    MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the GNU
X    Library General Public License for more details.
X    
X    You should have received a copy of the GNU Library General Public
X    License along with this library; if not, write to the Free Software
X    Foundation, Inc., 59 Temple Place, Suite 330, Boston, MA
X    02111-1307 USA
X
The complete distribution consists of the following files:
X
Makefile             a makefile which should facilitate the
X                     installation of this library.
COPYING.LIB          GNU Library General Public License (mentioned above).
README               short description of the routines of the library
X                     (necessary to make `library(help=Lasso2)' work
X                     in S-PLUS once the library is installed).
README.1st           you are just reading it ;-).
README.INSTALL       some information on how to install the library.
README.pd            README file which should go into the parent
X                     directory of the Lasso2 directory in which the
X                     library resides in the end (necessary so that
X                     `library()' will give the desired information in
X                     S-PLUS).
ChangeLog            history of the development of this library.
Doc                  a subdirectory with the manual and various
X                     supporting but unpublished manuscripts.
and the underlying C-engine:
X    lasso.c  lasso.h
the help files:
X    Iowa.d Prostate.d [.l1celist.d [[.l1celist.d aux.d aux.l1celist.d
X    coef.l1ce.d coef.l1celist.d deviance.gl1ce.d deviance.l1ce.d
X    deviance.l1celist.d fitted.l1ce.d fitted.l1celist.d gcv.d
X    gcv.l1ce.d gcv.l1celist.d gl1ce.d gl1ce.object.d is.formula.d
X    l1ce.d l1ce.object.d l1celist.object.d labels.l1ce.d
X    labels.l1celist.d merge.formula.d plot.l1celist.d predict.gl1ce.d
X    predict.l1ce.d print.gl1ce.d print.l1ce.d print.l1celist.d
X    print.summary.gl1ce.d print.summary.l1ce.d residuals.gl1ce.d
X    residuals.l1ce.d residuals.l1celist.d summary.gl1ce.d
X    summary.l1ce.d tr.d vcov.d vcov.l1ce.d vcov.l1celist.d
the S-Plus interface functions:
X    First.lib.q Iowa.q Prostate.q coef.q deviance.q fitted.q
X    force_ld.q formula.util.q gcv.q gl1ce.q l1ce.q labels.q misc.q
X    plot.q predict.q print.q residuals.q summary.q vcov.q
X
If you have any troubles or if you find any bugs in this library,
please let us know and we will try to fix them.  We would also be
interested to hear from you if you find this library useful and for
what kind of problems you are using it.

# ============= Lasso2/README.INSTALL ==============
if test -f 'Lasso2/README.INSTALL' && test X"$1" != X"-c"; then
  echo 'x - skipping Lasso2/README.INSTALL (File already exists)'
else
  echo 'x - extracting Lasso2/README.INSTALL (text)'
  sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > 'Lasso2/README.INSTALL' &&
This library was put together using the CHAPTER utility of S-PLUS.
This should make the installation process fairly simple.  The
development was done in a UNIX environment (also notable by the
filenames) and the instructions given here assume that a UNIX
environment is being used.  If the installation does not work then
please let me know.  Alternatively, you can use your own method of
installation.
X
INSTALLING THE LIBRARY:
X
Place the file Lasso2.shar in the directory of your choice.
X
For explanatory purposes, we will suppose that the directory has the
path name:
X                        ~/splus/libraries
X
Starting from this directory type the commands:
X
1) sh Lasso2.shar (This creates the directory Lasso2 underneath
X                   the current directory and unpacks all the required
X                   files)
2) cd Lasso2
X
3) Splus SHOME  (This tells you the location of the S-PLUS home
X                directory.  Next, edit the Makefile and make the SHOME
X                variable point to the location of this directory.
X                Also, change the WHICH_LOAD variable to the value
X                suitable for your system.  The description on using
X                the library given below assumes that you choose one of
X                the dynamic loading options.)
X
4) make install (This installs the S-PLUS functions and help files)
X
5) make load    (This makes the required object code)
X
6) make clean   (This deletes unnecessary files)
X
7) Does the parent directory (i.e. ~/splus/libraries) have a README
X   file?
X   yes:  Append the last line of README.pd to that file (and delete
X         README.pd) 
X   no:   type the following command:  mv README.pd ../README
X
X
USING THE LIBRARY:
X
Enter S-PLUS from any directory.  Assume that the absolute path for
X~/splus/libraries is /home/userxyz/splus/libraries.  To make the
Lasso2 functions available to the current session type:
X
X       assign("lib.loc","/home/userxyz/splus/libraries",where=0)
X       library(Lasso2)
X
To save having to type the first command each time you want to use
Lasso2 it is suggested that you create a .First function containing
these commands. It is then activated each time you enter S-PLUS.
X
SHAR_EOF
  $shar_touch -am 1209101399 'Lasso2/README.INSTALL' &&
  chmod 0644 'Lasso2/README.INSTALL' ||
  echo 'restore of Lasso2/README.INSTALL failed'

  test 2192 -eq "$shar_count" ||
    echo "Lasso2/README.INSTALL: original size 2192, current size $shar_count"
fi

begin 600 Lasso2/ChangeLog
